<header class="header">
  <h1>What Does a 50% Frost Probability Mean?</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Frost dates are risk markers — not guarantees.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    When you look up your average last frost date using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">frost date finder</a>,
    the date shown is typically based on a <strong>50% probability</strong> at the
    <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> freeze threshold.
    That number represents statistical risk — not certainty.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What 50% Probability Actually Means</h2>

  <p>
    A 50% frost probability means that, based on historical climate normals,
    there was a 50% chance temperatures reached 32°F (0°C) on or before that date.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Half of the recorded years were earlier.</li>
    <li>Half were later.</li>
    <li>It represents the statistical midpoint.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It does <strong>not</strong> mean frost will happen exactly on that day,
    nor does it mean frost will not occur after that day.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Climate Normals Use 50%</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are calculated from 30-year climate normals
    (1991–2020 in the U.S. and Canada).
  </p>

  <p>
    The 50% threshold provides:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>A stable planning anchor</li>
    <li>A balanced midpoint between early and late risk</li>
    <li>A consistent standard across regions</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It is useful for planning — but not a guarantee of safety.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Frost Dates Represent (And What They Don’t)</h2>

  <p>
    Your average last frost date represents the historical midpoint
    for freezing at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <p>
    It does not represent:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>The earliest frost ever recorded</li>
    <li>A guaranteed frost-free day</li>
    <li>Your exact yard’s microclimate</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Frost dates reduce guesswork — they do not eliminate risk.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Frost Dates Vary Year to Year</h2>

  <p>
    Even in stable climates, freeze timing shifts because of:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Late cold fronts</li>
    <li>Clear, calm nights that allow rapid cooling</li>
    <li>Snow cover patterns</li>
    <li>Cloud cover differences</li>
    <li>Soil moisture levels</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Some years will warm early and stay mild.
    Others will see freezing return after a warm stretch.
    This variability is normal and built into the 50% probability.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Conservatively vs Aggressively</h2>

  <h3>More Conservative Approach</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Plant warm-season crops after the average frost date.</li>
    <li>Use the later end of transplant windows.</li>
    <li>Wait for steady nighttime lows above freezing.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>More Aggressive Approach</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Plant near the average frost date.</li>
    <li>Use row cover for light frost risk.</li>
    <li>Accept some chance of replanting.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The right approach depends on your climate stability and risk tolerance.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why 32°F (0°C) Matters</h2>

  <p>
    The frost dates shown in the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">frost date finder</a>
    use the <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> freeze threshold.
  </p>

  <p>
    At this temperature:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Water in plant tissue can begin to freeze.</li>
    <li>Tender seedlings may suffer damage.</li>
    <li>Duration of cold becomes important.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Brief dips near freezing may cause minor damage.
    Prolonged freezes cause greater harm.
  </p>
</section>

